longside romances by Chaucer and Malory,to investigate the genre's reliance on individual and collective memorial processes. The author argues that a tale's objects, places, dreams, discoveries, disguises, prophecies, and dramatic ironies influence that romance's essential memory work, which relies as much on creativity as it does accuracy. He also explores the imaginative crafts of memory that are employed by romances themselves. Dr Jamie McKinstry teaches in the Department of English Studies at Durham University, where he is a member of the Institute of Medieval and Early Modern Studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEnglish poetryxHistory and criticismyMiddle English, 1100-1500. 0aEnglish poetryyMiddle English, 1100-1500xHistory and criticism. 0aMemory in literature. 0aRomances, EnglishxHistory and criticism. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aMiddle English romance.  aSir Gawain and the Green Knight.  aTroilus and Criseyde.  amedieval literature.  amemory analysis.  amemory challenges.  amemory depiction.  amemory exploration.  amemory function.  amemory work.  aromance analysis.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015z978311143132140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781782045861?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781782045861423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781782045861/original  a978-3-11-143132-1  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2015b2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles